SIMPLE: monarch
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Monarch
<hw>Mon"arch</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>monarque</ets>, L. <ets>monarcha</ets>, fr. Gr. <?/, <?/;
<grk>mo`nos</grk> alone + <?/ to be first, rule, govern. See
<er>Archi-</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A sole or supreme ruler; a
sovereign; the highest ruler; an emperor, king, queen, prince, or
chief.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He who reigns⟦br⟧
<qex>Monarch</qex> in heaven, . . . upheld by old repute.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>One superior to all others of the same kind; <as>as,
an oak is called the <ex>monarch</ex> of the forest</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A patron deity or presiding genius.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Come, thou, <qex>monarch</qex> of the vine,⟦br⟧
Plumpy Bacchus.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A very large red and black
butterfly (<spn>Danais Plexippus</spn>); -- called also
<altname>milkweed butterfly</altname> and <altname>monarch
butterfly</altname>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monarch</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Monarch
<hw>Mon"arch</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Superior to others; preeminent;
supreme; ruling.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Monarch</xex> savage.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Pope.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monarchal</ent>⟦br⟧
